#let images = (
  "8-1": (
    caption: [The CNS consists of the brain and spinal cord. Both structures are covered with meninges (脑膜) and bathed in cerebrospinal fluid (脑脊液, CSF). The diagram shows the cerebrum (大脑), cerebellum (小脑), spinal cord (脊髓), and meninges (脑膜) protecting these vital neural structures.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-2": (
    caption: [Embryonic development of the CNS. This dorsal view of a 22-day-old embryo shows transverse sections at three levels of the developing central nervous system, illustrating the neural tube (神经管), neural crest (神经嵴), and neural groove (神经沟) formation during early neurulation (神经形成).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-3": (
    caption: [The developmental sequence of the brain. (a) During the fourth week, three principal regions form: forebrain/prosencephalon (前脑), midbrain/mesencephalon (中脑), and hindbrain/rhombencephalon (后脑). (b) During the fifth week, five regions develop: telencephalon (端脑), diencephalon (间脑), mesencephalon, metencephalon (后脑), and myelencephalon (髓脑), showing the progressive differentiation of brain structures.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-4": (
    caption: [The ventricles of the brain. (a) An anterior view and (b) a lateral view showing the interconnected fluid-filled cavities: lateral ventricles (侧脑室), third ventricle (第三脑室), interventricular foramen (室间孔), mesencephalic aqueduct (中脑导水管), and fourth ventricle (第四脑室), all containing cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-5": (
    caption: [The cerebrum. (a) A lateral view and (b) a superior view displaying the two cerebral hemispheres (大脑半球) with characteristic gyri (脑回) and sulci (脑沟), representing the largest portion of the brain responsible for higher mental functions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-6": (
    caption: [The lobes of the left cerebral hemisphere. This diagram shows the four visible lobes: frontal lobe (额叶), parietal lobe (顶叶), temporal lobe (颞叶), and occipital lobe (枕叶), separated by major sulci including the central sulcus (中央沟) and lateral sulcus (外侧沟). Principal motor and sensory areas are indicated.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-7": (
    caption: [Motor and sensory areas of the cerebral cortex. (a) Motor areas controlling skeletal muscles are shown, specifically the primary motor cortex (初级运动皮层) in the precentral gyrus (中央前回). (b) Sensory areas receiving somatosensory sensations (躯体感觉) are shown in the postcentral gyrus (中央后回), demonstrating the somatotopic organization (体感定位组织) with body representation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-8": (
    caption: [An MRI image of the brain reveals the sensory cortex. The integration of MRI (magnetic resonance imaging, 磁共振成像) and EEG (electroencephalogram, 脑电图) information shows the precise location on the sensory cortex corresponding to each digit of the hand, demonstrating cortical mapping (皮层定位).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-9": (
    caption: [An MRI scan of the brain. Gray matter (灰质) and white matter (白质) are easily distinguished, as are the ventricles (脑室) containing cerebrospinal fluid. This imaging technique provides detailed visualization of brain anatomy and pathology.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-10": (
    caption: [Different types of waves in an electroencephalogram (EEG). Four distinct brain wave patterns are shown: alpha waves (α波, 8-13 Hz), beta waves (β波, 13-30 Hz), theta waves (θ波, 4-8 Hz), and delta waves (δ波, 0.5-4 Hz). Delta waves have the highest amplitude and lowest frequency, associated with deep sleep.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-11": (
    caption: [The basal nuclei (基底核). These subcortical structures include the caudate nucleus (尾状核), putamen (壳核), and globus pallidus (苍白球), collectively forming the corpus striatum (纹状体). They contain neurons involved in control of skeletal muscle movement (higher motor neurons). The thalamus (丘脑) serves as a relay center between motor cerebral cortex and other brain areas.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-12": (
    caption: [The motor circuit. This circuit is formed by interconnections between motor areas of the cerebral cortex, basal nuclei (basal ganglia, 基底神经节), and other brain regions. The diagram shows extensive inhibitory GABAergic effects (GABA能抑制效应) in red from the globus pallidus, while excitatory neurotransmitters include glutamate (谷氨酸, shown in green) and dopamine (多巴胺, shown in blue).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-13": (
    caption: [Different functions of the right and left cerebral hemispheres. These functional differences, termed cerebral lateralization (大脑侧化), were revealed by split-brain experiments. The left hemisphere specializes in language, analytical thinking, and logical reasoning, while the right hemisphere excels in spatial perception, pattern recognition, and holistic processing.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-14": (
    caption: [Brain areas involved in the control of speech. Key language areas include Broca's area (布洛卡区) in the frontal lobe for speech production and Wernicke's area (韦尼克区) in the temporal lobe for language comprehension. Damage to these areas produces speech deficits called aphasias (失语症): Broca's aphasia (表达性失语) and Wernicke's aphasia (接受性失语).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-15": (
    caption: [The limbic system (边缘系统). The left temporal lobe has been removed to show limbic structures in green, including the hippocampus (海马), amygdala (杏仁核), cingulate gyrus (扣带回), and septal nuclei (隔核). These structures are involved in emotion (情绪), memory formation (记忆形成), and motivation (动机).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-16": (
    caption: [Proposed mechanisms responsible for long-term potentiation (长期增强, LTP). The neurotransmitter glutamate (谷氨酸) binds to two different receptors: AMPA receptors (AMPA受体) and NMDA receptors (NMDA受体). LTP involves enhanced synaptic transmission and is crucial for learning and memory formation through mechanisms including receptor insertion and structural changes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-17": (
    caption: [Dendritic spines (树突棘). (a) A photomicrograph of a neuron from the human hippocampus showing dendrites. (b) Magnified view of dendritic spines - small protrusions on dendrites that receive synaptic inputs. These spines are highly plastic structures that change in number and morphology during learning and memory formation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-18": (
    caption: [Brain areas involved in emotion. (a) The orbitofrontal area (眶额皮层) of the prefrontal cortex in yellow, and the cingulate gyrus (扣带回) in blue-green (anterior) and green (posterior). (b) The insula (脑岛) in purple, anterior cingulate gyrus in blue-green, and amygdala (杏仁核) in red. These regions form an emotional processing network.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-19": (
    caption: [The adult brain in midsagittal section (正中矢状切面). This view reveals internal structures including the corpus callosum (胼胝体), thalamus (丘脑), hypothalamus (下丘脑), midbrain (中脑), pons (脑桥), medulla oblongata (延髓), cerebellum (小脑), and the ventricular system. The diencephalon (间脑) and telencephalon (端脑) regions are indicated.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-20": (
    caption: [Diagram of nuclei within the hypothalamus (下丘脑核团). The hypothalamic nuclei include the supraoptic nucleus (视上核), paraventricular nucleus (室旁核), anterior nucleus (前核), posterior nucleus (后核), and others. Each nucleus has specific functions in homeostasis (稳态), including temperature regulation, hunger, thirst, and hormone secretion control.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-21": (
    caption: [Dopaminergic pathways in the brain (多巴胺能通路). Two major pathways are shown: (1) The nigrostriatal system (黑质纹状体系统) from substantia nigra (黑质) to corpus striatum for motor control; (2) The mesolimbic system (中脑边缘系统) from midbrain to nucleus accumbens (伏隔核) and prefrontal cortex, involved in reward and motivation. Dysfunction of these pathways relates to Parkinson's disease and schizophrenia.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-22": (
    caption: [Respiratory control centers in the brain stem. Nuclei within the pons (脑桥) and medulla oblongata (延髓) control motor nerves required for breathing, including the pneumotaxic center (呼吸调整中枢), apneustic center (长吸中枢), and medullary rhythmicity center (延髓节律中枢). The reticular formation (网状结构) location is also indicated.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-23": (
    caption: [The reticular activating system (网状激活系统, RAS). Neural groups shown project to the thalamus, enhancing arousal (觉醒) of the cerebral cortex to sensory information. The RAS extends through the medulla, pons, and midbrain, playing a crucial role in consciousness (意识), sleep-wake cycles (睡眠-觉醒周期), and attention (注意力).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-24": (
    caption: [Ascending tracts carrying sensory information (上行感觉传导束). Third-order neurons deliver sensory information to the cerebral cortex. (a) Medial lemniscal tract (内侧丘系束) carries touch, pressure, and proprioception (本体感觉). (b) Lateral spinothalamic tract (外侧脊髓丘脑束) carries pain and temperature sensations. These pathways demonstrate decussation (交叉).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-25": (
    caption: [Descending corticospinal (pyramidal) motor tracts (下行皮质脊髓束/锥体束). These tracts contain axons passing from the precentral gyrus (motor cortex) down the spinal cord to synapse with spinal interneurons and motor neurons. Most fibers cross at the pyramidal decussation (锥体交叉) in the medulla, explaining contralateral motor control (对侧运动控制).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-26": (
    caption: [Higher motor neuron control of skeletal muscles. The pyramidal (corticospinal) tracts (锥体束) in pink provide direct voluntary motor control. The extrapyramidal tracts (锥体外系) descending from the brain stem control posture, balance, and involuntary movements. Both systems converge on lower motor neurons in the spinal cord.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-27": (
    caption: [Distribution of the spinal nerves (脊神经). The 31 pairs of spinal nerves interconnect at plexuses (神经丛) - cervical plexus (颈丛), brachial plexus (臂丛), lumbar plexus (腰丛), and sacral plexus (骶丛) - and form specific peripheral nerves that innervate different body regions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "8-28": (
    caption: [Activation of somatic motor neurons (躯体运动神经元). Somatic motor neurons can be stimulated by spinal association neurons (脊髓联络神经元) or directly by sensory neurons in a reflex arc (反射弧) that doesn't involve the brain. They can also be stimulated by upper motor neurons (上运动神经元) from brain motor areas, providing voluntary control over reflexes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-8-1": (
    caption: [Functions of the Cerebral Lobes. This table summarizes the primary functions associated with each lobe: frontal lobe (voluntary motor control, speech production, higher cognitive functions), parietal lobe (somatosensory processing, spatial awareness), temporal lobe (auditory processing, language comprehension, memory), occipital lobe (visual processing), and insula (taste, visceral sensations, emotional awareness).],
